    "description": "Evolocumab is a monoclonal antibody that inhibits PCSK9 (proprotein convertase subtilisin/kexin type 9), a protein that reduces the liver's ability to remove LDL cholesterol from the blood. By preventing PCSK9 from binding to LDL receptors on liver cells, Evolocumab effectively lowers levels of LDL cholesterol, which is a significant risk factor for cardiovascular diseases. It is primarily used in patients with hyperlipidemia or those who are unable to achieve target LDL cholesterol levels with diet and statin therapy alone.",
    "uses": "Evolocumab is employed in the management of conditions such as familial hypercholesterolemia, a genetic disorder causing high cholesterol levels, and also for patients with atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease who require additional LDL cholesterol lowering. It may be prescribed for individuals who have had heart attacks or strokes and continue to have high LDL cholesterol despite maximum tolerated doses of statins and lifestyle changes.\n\nIn addition, Evolocumab is used in a variety of populations, including adults with mixed dyslipidemia, offering benefits for those with complex lipid disorders. It may also be considered in patients who cannot tolerate statins due to side effects, providing a valuable alternative for cholesterol management.",
